			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">The truth was hazy because:
<br />

<br />
1.  We didn't know what happened to the people in her unit.
<br />
2.  She was badly injured.
<br />
3.  She reportedly did not recall the events.
<br />

<br />
Newspeople despise a vacuum...so...the haziness was filled with "expanded" details...encouraged by the armed forces desire to present a positive war story.  The armed forces are sensitive to women being in harm's way because there is a substantial political constituency that is opposed (to different degrees) to women in combat roles.  This led them to publicize the rescue...it shows they did something about it.
<br />

<br />
A number of members of her unit DID lose their lives.  Every prisoner of war that does not compromise our mission is a hero.  Every injured warrior, male or female, is a hero.  She may not be MORE deserving than others, but she is AS deserving as any other in the same situation.
<br />

<br />
I don't think there was any intention to mislead either from the government or the press.  There was an intention from the armed forces to use the event for propaganda purposes...but as in my earlier argument propaganda is not a bad thing.  We would fail in any military mission without the political support of the people of this republic.  It is critical that information is given to them that demonstrates both our progress and our response to setbacks.
<br />

<br />
Wolen
<br />

<br />
P.S. Deris--Don't think I am ignoring your points.  Every single serviceman and servicewoman that serves honorably DESERVES the same adulation and praise that PFC Lynch received.  That just isn't how the world works.  But the God who is invisible sees and rewards that which men do not see and reward.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
