				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">The word 'hero' has such a broad range of connotations.  It is used generically by politicians to honor those that take on service that others avoid.  I don't think it is a misappropriation of the term to call PFC Lynch a hero from that viewpoint.  Remember...we refer to ALL of our servicepeople as heroes on Memorial Day and Veteran's Day.
<br />

<br />
I hear where you're going by saying she isn't "all that special" and isn't deserving of the SECOND kind of hero status--a person known for going beyond normal human limitations to accomplish something different and noteworthy.  We can't say for sure but this far after the fact her action under fire doesn't seem to be a cut above...but her actions are honorable just the same.
<br />

<br />
The last thing is that she got singled out for attention that others deserve as well.  I look at this two ways...she represents all of the armed forces in accepting that adulation (all the way up until the second she makes a penny from it.)  And the armed forces as a whole are better off if their duty and sacrifices gain attention...even if it is through overhyping one person's situation.
<br />

<br />
Not disagreeing with others positions...just clarifying precisely where I'm coming from.
<br />

<br />
Wolen<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
