				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Western man's protective nature. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
Dunno why you stress that point, most of the US Military will rescue a POW female or male, and as a Marine one of our motto's is 'No one gets left behind', and we happen to borrow that from the HMRM (Her Majesty's Royal Marines), and I don't consider Britain a 'western' nation, but ok <img src="images/smiles/badrazz.gif" alt="badrazz" border="0" /> i'll bite.
<br />

<br />
And yes Chakan that word is thrown around entirely too much and retardedly. Back in WWII or Vietnam a hero was someone who did something that will be remembered for quite some time. I'm just doing my job, I don't do anything heroic on a day to day basis, and by all accounts I haven't heard of anything thats really outstanding that was done in Iraq. 
<br />

<br />
A Hero in my eyes is someone that does something above and beyond the call of duty, making a tough decision to do something that would put him in , without a doubt, deadly harm, to accomplish a goal.
<br />

<br />
a Medal of Honor winner is usually touted as a hero, and I can remember most of the really good stories, and they're usually a testament to the power of human will, showing that we truly can persevere and push the limits, physically and mentally. Some of those stories when told first hand have been enough to make me cry. 
<br />

<br />
The Army is trying to almost (4th highest honor) compare PFC Lynch with one of these icons of human perseverence? Not on my @#%$ watch. Its stupid, inane and lame how people hand medals out like candy now, they used to mean something. I've heard that I will be getting a big fat @#%$ stack of medals and ribbons just for being in country, when I've heard maybe 3 shots fired, far far away, and haven't even seen a corpse or actually locked and loaded yet? Stupidity. the dumbing down of the armed forces is sad.<span class="gensmall"></span>


